==English==

===Etymology===
{{borrowing|fro|embellir|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɪmˈbɛlɪʃ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-embellish.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|es}}

# To make more [[beautiful]] and [[attractive]]; to [[decorate]].
#: ''The old book cover was '''embellished''' with golden letters''
#* {{quote-journal|author=Paul Doyle|title=Arsenal's Theo Walcott hits hat-trick in thrilling victory over Newcastle||url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2012/dec/29/arsenal-newcastle-united-premier-league|newspaper={{w|The Guardian}}|city=London|date=29 December 2012|passage=Podolski gave Walcott a chance to further '''embellish''' Arsenal's first-half performance when he eluded James Perch and slipped the ball through to the striker.}}
# To make something sound or look [[better]] or more [[acceptable]] than it is in reality, to [[distort]].
#: ''to '''embellish''' a story, the truth''

